body:
I can reproduce this issue:
_Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/tmp/benchmarks/scripts/tf_cnn_benchmarks/preprocessing.py", line 1072, in create_dataset
    import ssd_dataloader  # pylint: disable=g-import-not-at-top
  File "/tmp/benchmarks/scripts/tf_cnn_benchmarks/ssd_dataloader.py", line 27, in <module>
    from object_detection.box_coders import faster_rcnn_box_coder
ImportError: No module named 'object_detection'_

I figured out that in step 1 of the instructions you git clone https://github.com/tensorflow/models.git
hence creating a directory "models". In step 6  you git clone https://github.com/IntelAI/models.git creating another "models" directory. These two directories should be renamed ~/tensorflowmodels and ~/IntelAImodels and kept independent of each other. This solution solves the "no module name object_detection for me."

Then further down the process, I eventually run in another error while loading the first image file from COCO dataset:
tensorflow.python.framework.errors_impl_InvalidArgumentError: StringToNumberOp could not correctly convert string: 00000379133.jpg [[{{node StringToNumber}}]] [[batch_processing/IteratorGetNext]]
The parser seems to not extract the integer from the file name..

Hi,
The instructions for accuracy measurements state to run:

python launch_benchmark.py
--data-location /home/user/coco/output/
--in-graph /home/user/ssd_resnet34_fp32_bs1_pretrained_model.pb
--model-source-dir /home/user/tensorflow/models
--model-name ssd-resnet34
--framework tensorflow
--precision fp32
--mode inference
--socket-id 0
--batch-size=1
--docker-image gcr.io/deeplearning-platform-release/tf-cpu.1-14
--accuracy-only

It differs from benchmark-only by adding reference to the COCO data set with –data-location.
What the docker script is really doing I did not reverse engineer.




The instructions state to run

But why do you need to load the raw jpg images when running the inference?

—

Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub<https://github.com/IntelAI/models/issues/29?email_source=notifications&email_token=ALOFB6ZM4S5Q3XHDHTNS4TLQB7IGTA5CNFSM4IG7ABL2YY3PNVWWK3TUL52HS4DFVREXG43VMVBW63LNMVXHJKTDN5WW2ZLOORPWSZGOD3C2ZLI#issuecomment-516271277>, or mute the thread<https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/ALOFB66KLFILBMZX7BEOPJLQB7IGTANCNFSM4IG7ABLQ>.

@hubertdelassus 
Find a solution to solve the problem, please refer to this issue: https://github.com/tensorflow/benchmarks/issues/408
and the pr request:
https://github.com/tensorflow/benchmarks/pull/409

@hubertdelassus 
Find the root cause,
In the BKM, it suggest to use this commit id:7a9934df2afdf95be9405b4e9f1f2480d748dc40
of create_coco_tf_record.py to convert the data into tfrecord format.
However, in this commit-id, it use filename(*.jpg) as source-id.
```
157       'image/source_id': dataset_util.bytes_feature(
158           filename.encode('utf8')),
```
That's why our benchmark failed at StringToNumberOp .

The latest create_coco_tf_record.py  will use image_id as the source-id.
```
      'image/source_id':
          dataset_util.bytes_feature(str(image_id).encode('utf8')),
```
Using the  latest create_coco_tf_record.py  ,  it will fix your issue.

The origin README.md suggested to use the old commit of create_coco_tf_record.py to create the COCO dataset in tfrecord format.
It would cause the problem as this issue: https://github.com/IntelAI/models/issues/29
Combining the BKM of the origin author: https://github.com/tensorflow/benchmarks/issues/262
I make this changes of BKM.
With this new one I can run the accuracy testing get similar accuracy results as in the BKM.

Thanks Leslie for addressing this issue in a diligent manner. I tested the fix and the images are now read properly. However the resnet34-ssd benchmark script in accuracy-only still fails when starting inference. I opened another ticket for this separate issue.

We recently released model workload containers for SSD-ResNet34 [FP32](https://software.intel.com/content/www/us/en/develop/articles/containers/ssd-resnet34-fp32-inference-tensorflow-container.html) and [Int8](https://software.intel.com/content/www/us/en/develop/articles/containers/ssd-resnet34-int8-inference-tensorflow-container.html) inference. These containers have all the code, dependency installs, and pretrained models needed to run the inference and accuracy scripts. All that you'll need to provide is the [preprocessed COCO dataset](https://github.com/IntelAI/models/tree/master/datasets/coco) and an output directory where log files will be written. The links above have instructions on how to run the containers for accuracy and inference. I ran these scripts for both FP32 and Int8 (both accuracy and inference scripts) to verify that they are working. The containers have "quick start scripts" (which are described in the docs), which make it easier to run common use cases. If you want to call the launch_benchmark.py script with your own args, you can still do that by giving the `python benchmarks/launch_benchmark.py ...` command instead of the quickstart script in the docker run command. For more information on how to do this, please see the [advanced container usages documentation](https://github.com/IntelAI/models/blob/master/quickstart/common/tensorflow/ModelPackagesAdvancedOptions.md#docker).
Closing since it's been over 90 days with no activity
